<DOC><DOCNO> AP890626-0111 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1358EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a PM-TropicalWeather 3rdLd-Writethru a0533 06-26 0369</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Tropical Weather, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0533,0377</SECOND><HEAD>Season's First Tropical Storm Brings Heavy Rain to Texas Coast</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with storm strength, position, evacuation.No pickup.</HEAD><DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The first tropical storm of the season developedin the Gulf of Mexico this morning, bringing heavy rain and floodingto the Texas coast.   The National Hurricane Center in Coral Gables, Fla., upgraded aslow-moving tropical depression to a storm about 7 a.m. after itssustained winds reached 39 mph.   By late morning, Tropical Storm Allison had sustained near 50 mphwith gusts to 65 mph, the National Weather Service said. It wasmoving north about 5 mph and was southwest of Freeport, about 55miles south of Houston.   A voluntary evacuation was issued for Quintana Beach, a smallisland community of about 150 south of Houston. Sheriff's deputieswent door-to-door telling residents that rising waters could closethe bridge to the mainland.   ``We're telling them if they want to get out, they'd better getout now,'' Chief Deputy Charles Wagner said.   Tides in Galveston were about three feet above normal.   ``There probably will be some minor wind damage. The main thingis the rain. It's a heavy rainmaker,'' National Weather Servicemeteorologist Larry Vannozzi said.   A tropical storm warning was issued from Freeport to Morgan City,La. There were reports of flooding south of Galveston, Matagorda andBrazoria.   Rain drenched the coast, with as much as 6 inches reported frommidnight to midmorning. A flash flood watch was in effect for muchof the southeast Texas coast.   In Louisiana, shrimp fishermen stayed home and tourists wereurged to avoid coastal areas. ``It's not really nasty here _ yet,''Calcasieu Parish, La., Deputy Bradley Fontenot said. ``They say it'sgoing to be.''   On Sunday, the Galveston County beach patrol banned swimming.``It's got the gulf kicked up pretty nasty out there right now,''patrol director Vic Maceo said.   In Corpus Christi, some residents waited to take precautions.   ``The surfing and wind surfing are real popular today _ they'reout there right now,'' police dispatcher Richard Diaz said Sunday.   The tropical depression had its origins in Hurricane Cosme, whichmoved from the Pacific Ocean across Mexico last week.</TEXT></DOC>